45":"1045","1100":"1100","about 1075":"circa 1075","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Estouteville, Normandy, France":"Estouteville, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1075–1140":"about 1075–1140","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1088–Male":"1088–Deceased","1091–Male":"1091–Deceased","1100–1172":"1100–1172","1112–Female":"1112–Deceased","–1191":"–1191","1040–1107":"1040–1107","1045–Female":"1045–Deceased","1091":"1091","1385":"1385","1088":"1088","1075":"1075","1140":"1140","1040":"1040","1172":"1172","1191":"1191","1107":"1107","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","about 1075":"about 1075","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Estouteville, Normandy, France":"Estouteville, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stuteville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Estouteville or Etoutteville in Seine-Maritime."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"lll","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  Sanskrit: a term of endearment, ‘darling boy’.","2  Prakrit: ‘king’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert lll de Stuteville was born about 1075, in Estouteville, Normandy, France, his father, Robert ll d'Estouteville, was 37 and his mother, Beatrix of Valmont, was 32. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1140, in Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1075–1140":"umbes 1075–1140","1075–1140":"1075–1140","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1091–Male":"1091–Surnud","1100–1172":"1100–1172","1112–Female":"1112–Surnud","–1191":"–1191","1040–1107":"1040–1107","1045–Female":"1045–Surnud","1091":"1091","1385":"1385","1088":"1088","1075":"1075","1140":"1140","1040":"1040","1172":"1172","1191":"1191","1107":"1107","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Marit